Line Street Maps - OSM Data

Will Ball

22/12/2020

Line Street Maps

This document explains how to create line street maps using OSM data and ggplot2. Its based on this great tutorial by Christian Burkhart.

There are four general steps required:

  1. Load in the necessary packages
  2. Store the data in objects
  3. Plot the line objects
  4. Save the plot

The Packages

Were using data from Open Street Map which can be downloaded using the {osmdata} package. We also need {ggplot2} and the {magrittr} forward pipe operator (%>%) so we might as well call the whole {tidyverse} package.Finally, some of these functions take a little while (depending on the size of the city/area you are plotting & how detailed/large the saved file is) so Ive also loaded {beepr} which is a package with a single function, beep(), that you can add to the end of your code which makes a handy noise once its complete.

If you dont have these packages already installed, you should use install.packages("packagename") before loading them using the library function.

library(osmdata)
library(tidyverse)
library(beepr)

The Data

First, we collect Open Street Map data on main streets, small streets and any rivers that we want to plot.

area <- "Paris, France" # Insert city/area name here within speech marks

streets <- getbb(area) %>%
  opq() %>%
  add_osm_feature(key = "highway", 
                  value = c("motorway", "primary", 
                            "secondary", "tertiary")) %>%
  osmdata_sf()

small_streets <- getbb(area) %>%
  opq() %>%
  add_osm_feature(key = "highway", 
                  value = c("residential", "living_street",
                            "unclassified",
                            "service", "footway")) %>%
  osmdata_sf()

river <- getbb(area) %>%
  opq() %>%
  add_osm_feature(key = "waterway", value = "river") %>%
  osmdata_sf()

a <- getbb(area) # Creates an object that lists the boundary box limits for the area
beep("coin")

The Plot

Here we plot the data extracted above. Each one forms a geom_sf. We can specify the colour, size and opacity (alpha) of each of the lines as well as the.

(p <- ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = streets$osm_lines,
          inherit.aes = FALSE,
          color = "white",
          size = .4,
          alpha = .6) +
  geom_sf(data = small_streets$osm_lines,
          inherit.aes = FALSE,
          color = "#D14702",
          size = .2,
          alpha = .4) +
  geom_sf(data = river$osm_lines,
          inherit.aes = FALSE,
          color = "#0062FF",
          size = .3,
          alpha = .8) +
  coord_sf(xlim = c(a[1], a[3]), 
           ylim = c(a[2], a[4]),
           expand = FALSE) +
    theme_void() +
   theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "#282828")) # Remove this line if you want the background blank
)
beep("coin")

Save

Now to save the plot. Dont forget to change the file name.

ggsave(filename = "ParisDark.png", plot = p, height = 3, width = 3, units = "in", dpi = 500)

beep("coin")
